@title   UniswapV3 Vault
 @notice  A vault that provides liquidity on Uniswap V3.
@dev Withdraws share of liquidity in a range from Uniswap pool.

@dev Withdraws liquidity from a range and collects all fees in the
 process.
@dev Deposits liquidity in a range on the Uniswap pool.
@notice Balance of token0 in vault not used in any position.
@notice Balance of token1 in vault not used in any position.
@dev Wrapper around `IUniswapV3Pool.positions()`.
@dev Wrapper around `LiquidityAmounts.getAmountsForLiquidity()`.
@dev Wrapper around `LiquidityAmounts.getLiquidityForAmounts()`.
@dev Casts uint256 to uint128 with overflow check.
@dev Callback for Uniswap V3 pool.
@dev Callback for Uniswap V3 pool.
@notice Used to collect accumulated protocol fees.
@notice Removes tokens accidentally sent to this vault.

@notice Used to change the protocol fee charged on pool fees earned from
 Uniswap, expressed as multiple of 1e-6.

@notice Used to change deposit cap for a guarded launch or to ensure
 vault doesn't grow too large relative to the pool. Cap is on total
 supply rather than amounts of token0 and token1 as those amounts
 fluctuate naturally over time.
@notice Removes liquidity in case of emergency.

@notice Governance address is not updated until the new governance
 address has called `acceptGovernance()` to accept this responsibility.

@notice `setGovernance()` should be called by the existing governance
 address prior to calling this function.

approve(address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-approve}. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address.

constructor.details: After deploying, manager needs to be set via `setManager()`

params._protocolFee: Protocol fee expressed as multiple of 1e-6

decimals().details: Returns the number of decimals used to get its user representation. For example, if `decimals` equals `2`, a balance of `505` tokens should be displayed to a user as `5,05` (`505 / 10 ** 2`). Tokens usually opt for a value of 18, imitating the relationship between Ether and Wei. This is the value {ERC20} uses, unless {_setupDecimals} is called. NOTE: This information is only used for _display_ purposes: it in no way affects any of the arithmetic of the contract, including {IERC20-balanceOf} and {IERC20-transfer}.

decreaseAllowance(address,uint256).details: Atomically decreases the allowance granted to `spender` by the caller. This is an alternative to {approve} that can be used as a mitigation for problems described in {IERC20-approve}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address. - `spender` must have allowance for the caller of at least `subtractedValue`.

deposit(uint256,uint256,uint256,uint256,.details: These tokens sit in the vault and are not used for liquidity on Uniswap until the next rebalance. Also note it's not necessary to check if user manipulated price to deposit cheaper, as the value of range orders can only by manipulated higher.

params.amount0Desired: Max amount of token0 to deposit
params.amount0Min: Revert if resulting `amount0` is less than this
params.amount1Desired: Max amount of token1 to deposit
params.amount1Min: Revert if resulting `amount1` is less than this

increaseAllowance(address,uint256).details: Atomically increases the allowance granted to `spender` by the caller. This is an alternative to {approve} that can be used as a mitigation for problems described in {IERC20-approve}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address.

name().details: Returns the name of the token.

rebalance(int256,uint160,int24,int24,int.details: Two orders are placed - a base order and a limit order. The base order is placed first with as much liquidity as possible. This order should use up all of one token, leaving only the other one. This excess amount is then placed as a single-sided bid or ask order.

symbol().details: Returns the symbol of the token, usually a shorter version of the name.

transfer(address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-transfer}. Requirements: - `recipient` cannot be the zero address. - the caller must have a balance of at least `amount`.

transferFrom(address,address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-transferFrom}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. This is not required by the EIP. See the note at the beginning of {ERC20}. Requirements: - `sender` and `recipient` cannot be the zero address. - `sender` must have a balance of at least `amount`. - the caller must have allowance for ``sender``'s tokens of at least `amount`.

params.amount0Min: Revert if resulting `amount0` is smaller than this
params.amount1Min: Revert if resulting `amount1` is smaller than this

returns.amount0: Amount of token0 sent to recipient
returns.amount1: Amount of token1 sent to recipient

acceptGovernance().notice: `setGovernance()` should be called by the existing governance address prior to calling this function.

collectProtocol(uint256,uint256,address).notice: Used to collect accumulated protocol fees.

deposit(uint256,uint256,uint256,uint256,.notice: Deposits tokens in proportion to the vault's current holdings.

emergencyBurn(int24,int24,uint128).notice: Removes liquidity in case of emergency.

getBalance0().notice: Balance of token0 in vault not used in any position.

getBalance1().notice: Balance of token1 in vault not used in any position.

getPositionAmounts(int24,int24).notice: Amounts of token0 and token1 held in vault's position. Includes owed fees but excludes the proportion of fees that will be paid to the protocol. Doesn't include fees accrued since last poke.

getTotalAmounts().notice: Calculates the vault's total holdings of token0 and token1 - in other words, how much of each token the vault would hold if it withdrew all its liquidity from Uniswap.

rebalance(int256,uint160,int24,int24,int.notice: Updates vault's positions. Can only be called by the manager.

setGovernance(address).notice: Governance address is not updated until the new governance address has called `acceptGovernance()` to accept this responsibility.

setManager(address).notice: Used to set the manager contract that determines the position ranges and calls rebalance(). Must be called after this vault is deployed.

setMaxTotalSupply(uint256).notice: Used to change deposit cap for a guarded launch or to ensure vault doesn't grow too large relative to the pool. Cap is on total supply rather than amounts of token0 and token1 as those amounts fluctuate naturally over time.

setProtocolFee(uint256).notice: Used to change the protocol fee charged on pool fees earned from Uniswap, expressed as multiple of 1e-6.

sweep(address,uint256,address).notice: Removes tokens accidentally sent to this vault.

withdraw(uint256,uint256,uint256,address.notice: Withdraws tokens in proportion to the vault's holdings.

userdoc.notice: A vault that provides liquidity on Uniswap V3.
